06058nam a22009615i 9780520969131DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019018669  a97805209691317 a10.1525/97805209691312doi  a(DE-B1597)540122  a(OCoLC)1117645661  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aE185.86 4aE185.86b.C547 2019 7aSOC0010002bisacsh04a305.5508960730747212231 aClerge, Orly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New Noir :bRace, Identity, and Diaspora in Black Suburbia /cOrly Clerge. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface: Aperitif -- t1. Village Market: Encounters in Black Diasporic Suburbs -- t2. Children of the Yam: From Enslaved African to the Black Middle Class in the United States, Haiti, and Jamaica -- t3. Blood Pudding: Forbidden Neighbors on Jim Crow Long Island -- t4. Callaloo: Cultural Economies of our Backyards -- t5. Fish Soup: Class Journey across Time and Place -- t6. Vanilla Black: The Spectrum of Racial Consciousness -- t7. Green Juice Fast: Skinfolk Distinction Making -- tConclusion: Mustard Seeds -- tAppendix: Digestif -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe expansion of the Black American middle class and the unprecedented increase in the number of Black immigrants since the 1960s have transformed the cultural landscape of New York. In The New Noir, Orly Clerge explores the richly complex worlds of an extraordinary generation of Black middle class adults who have migrated from different corners of the African diaspora to suburbia. The Black middle class today consists of diverse groups whose ongoing cultural, political, and material ties to the American South and Global South shape their cultural interactions at work, in their suburban neighborhoods, and at their kitchen tables. Clerge compellingly analyzes the making of a new multinational Black middle class and how they create a spectrum of Black identities that help them carve out places of their own in a changing 21st-century global city. Paying particular attention to the largest Black ethnic groups in the country, Black Americans, Jamaicans, and Haitians, Clerge's ethnography draws on over 80 interviews with residents to examine the overlooked places where New York's middle class resides in Queens and Long Island. This book reveals that region and nationality shape how the Black middle class negotiates the everyday politics of race and class.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAfrican diasporaxSocial conditions. 0aImmigrantszNew York (State)zLong Island. 0aImmigrantszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aMiddle class African AmericanszNew York (State)zLong IslandxSocial conditions. 0aMiddle class African AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditions. 0aMiddle class African AmericanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocialconditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  a1960s.  a21st century.  aafrican american middle class.  aafrican diaspora.  aamerican south.  ablack american middle class.  ablack identities.  ablack immigrants.  acultural interactions.  acultural landscape.  aculture.  adiverse groups.  aglobal south.  along island.  amultinational black middle class.  anew york.  apolitical.  aqueens.  arace issues.  arace politics.  asuburban neighborhoods.  asuburbia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iT